Directory services help manage users, computers, and access to network based resources. They provide a way to manage and store user identities, ensuring only authorized users can access specific files, applications, and systems. Organizations use directory services to simplify authentication, enforce security policies, and help streamline access to local and cloud-based resources.

In IT support, different directory services help users log in to computers, access network drives, use cloud applications, and interact with shared resources. The four most common directory services are:
Local Users and Groups
Active Directory
Entra ID
AWS IAM 

Local Users and Groups is a basic directory service available on individual computers, especially in standalone systems not connected to a centralized domain.

Active Directory, shown in the figure, is Microsoft’s centralized directory service used in enterprise environments. It runs on Windows Server and allows centralized management of users, computers, groups, and security policies.

Local Users = one computer
Active Directory = whole network

Entra ID, shown in the figure, is Microsoft’s cloud-based identity and access management (IAM) service. It’s designed for modern cloud applications and integrates seamlessly with Microsoft 365, Azure, and thousands of Software as a Service (SaaS) applications.

Amazon Web Services (AWS) IAM is a cloud-native directory service designed to manage access to AWS resources. Unlike traditional directory services, IAM focuses on permissions for cloud infrastructure, applications, and services within the AWS ecosystem.

Multifactor Authentication
Connecting to directory services requires authentication. Traditionally, this meant entering just a username and password. However, it has become more common to require multifactor authentication (MFA) to improve security.
